{"status":"success","result":"What did Claude CLI say? I'm curious whether we're aligned or if there's a different angle worth considering.\n\nMy instinct on what's *safely* offloadable to the Secretary — meaning low risk if it gets it slightly wrong:\n\n*Good candidates:*\n• Task classification (what I described)\n• Response format validation — \"does this reply use correct Telegram formatting?\" quick pass before sending\n• Memory update drafting — Secretary proposes what to write to jarvis.md, Jarvis just commits it\n• Clarifying question generation — when input is ambiguous, Secretary drafts \"did you mean X or Y?\" rather than Jarvis burning cycles on it\n\n*Borderline — depends on accuracy needs:*\n• Pre-flight capability check — \"does this need tools or pure chat?\" — workable but 4b will occasionally misclassify edge cases\n• Error message simplification — rewording tool errors into plain language before surfacing to user\n\n*Should stay with Jarvis or higher:*\n• Anything where a wrong answer has consequences — decisions, code review, anything the user will act on\n• Long context tasks — Secretary has 8k context limit, easy to overflow\n• Synthesis — combining results from multiple sources needs more than 4b reasoning\n\nThe pattern I'd apply as a rule: *Secretary handles shape, not substance.* It can decide *how* to route or *format* something, but never *what* the answer is.\n\nWhat did CLI suggest? I want to know if there's overlap or if it went somewhere I didn't.","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
